name: libtorrent
description: an efficient feature complete C++ bittorrent implementation
description_good_justification:
https://libtorrent.org
"libtorrent is a feature complete C++ bittorrent implementation focusing on efficiency and scalability."
contribution_justification: Projects on GitHub by default use issues and pull requests, as encouraged by documentation such as <https://guides.github.com/activities/contributing-to-open-source/>.
license_location_justification: Non-trivial license location file in repository: <https://github.com/arvidn/libtorrent/blob/RC_1_2/COPYING>.
floss_license_justification:
all code is released under the BSD license, as documented here: <https://github.com/arvidn/libtorrent/blob/master/LICENSE>
dependencies are released under the boost license: <https://opensource.org/licenses/BSL-1.0> The BSD-3-Clause license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
floss_license_osi_justification: The BSD-3-Clause license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
documentation_basics_justification:
online documentation: <https://libtorrent.org/reference.html>
documentation source files in repo: <https://github.com/arvidn/libtorrent/tree/master/docs>
repo_public_justification: Repository on GitHub, which provides public git repositories with URLs.
repo_track_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git can track the changes, who made them, and when they were made.
repo_interim_justification: project uses git tags to mark releases: <https://github.com/arvidn/libtorrent/releases>
repo_distributed_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git is distributed.
release_notes_justification: Non-trivial release notes file in repository: <https://github.com/arvidn/libtorrent/blob/master/ChangeLog>.
report_tracker_justification: github issue tracker is enabled and in use: <https://github.com/arvidn/libtorrent/issues>
report_process_justification: github issue tracker is enabled and in use: <https://github.com/arvidn/libtorrent/issues>. There is also a mailing list hosted by source forge: <https://sourceforge.net/projects/libtorrent/lists/libtorrent-discuss>
report_archive_justification: all github issues as well as the mailing list archive are public: <https://github.com/arvidn/libtorrent/issues?utf8=%E2%9C%93&q=is%3Aissue+> <https://sourceforge.net/p/libtorrent/mailman/libtorrent-discuss/>
vulnerability_report_process_justificati: vulnerabilities are reported either via mailing list or github issue tracker: <https://github.com/arvidn/libtorrent/issues>
vulnerability_report_response_justificat: all vulnerabilities with CVEs have been responded to swiftly, as well as OSS-Fuzz issues.
build_floss_tools_justification: boost-build, gcc and clang are all supported
test_justification: <https://github.com/arvidn/libtorrent/tree/master/test> and <https://github.com/arvidn/libtorrent/tree/master/simulation>, both run as part of CI.
test_invocation_justification: tests are built and run by boost-build as well as cmake
test_policy_justification: test coverage is measured as part of CI <https://codecov.io/gh/arvidn/libtorrent>
tests_documented_added_justification: test policy is documented in the contribution document <https://github.com/arvidn/libtorrent/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.rst>
warnings_justification: the CI build enabled `-Weverything` on clang <https://github.com/arvidn/libtorrent/blob/master/Jamfile#L213> and `-Wall` along with additional warning flags on GCC <https://github.com/arvidn/libtorrent/blob/master/Jamfile#L228> and the highest warning level on msvc: <https://github.com/arvidn/libtorrent/blob/master/Jamfile#L240>
warnings_strict_justification: all warnings are enabled (except for a few on msvc) <https://github.com/arvidn/libtorrent/blob/master/Jamfile#L210>
know_common_errors_justification: 20+ years of experiencing bugs in C++ software.
crypto_published_justification: the bittorrent protocol does not use any cryptographic primitives. There is however support for encrypted bittorrent swarms in libtorrent, as an extension. But it cannot be on by default.
crypto_call_justification: the main crypto dependency is libcrypto, or other OS-native crypto libraries.
crypto_keylength_justification: The only keys used in bittorrent are for SSL, which supports everything openSSL does. the ed25519 keys used in the DHT mutable puts are 32 bytes (256 bits)
crypto_working_justification: All crypto is done by openssl (some obfuscation is done using RC4, but is not advertised as providing any confidentiality)
crypto_pfs_justification: the only confidential channels are implemented by OpenSSL.
crypto_password_storage_justification: there is no storing of passwords or keys.
crypto_random_justification: in the extension to run bittorrent over SSL, the private keys are loaded from specific and individual files
delivery_mitm_justification: The only relevant case is bittorrent over SSL, where all peers have certificates signed by the certificate authority.
delivery_unsigned_justification: typically bittorrent receives a *trusted* SHA-1 hash from the user, and it's outside of the scope of the library to authenticate that the user can trust the source.
vulnerabilities_fixed_60_days_justificat: All CVEs have been patched quickly in the past
vulnerabilities_critical_fixed_justifica: All bug reports get a response and possibly a patch.
static_analysis_justification:
clang-tidy, cpplint.py, sonarcube and LGTM are used for static analysis. The first two block pull requests on failures.
sonarcube: <https://sonarcloud.io/dashboard?id=libtorrent>
LGTM: <https://lgtm.com/projects/g/arvidn/libtorrent/>
<https://github.com/arvidn/libtorrent/blob/master/.travis.yml#L225> <https://github.com/arvidn/libtorrent/blob/master/.travis.yml#L238>
static_analysis_fixed_justification: they are mostly addressed before a PR lands, as PRs are blocked by CI failures.
static_analysis_often_justification: all of clang-tidy, cpplint.py and sonar cube run on every commit as well as every pull request prior to landing.
dynamic_analysis_justification: all tests are run with clang sanitizers enabled (address sanitizer and undefined sanitizer).
dynamic_analysis_unsafe_justification: oss-fuzz runs fuzzers continuously for the project <https://oss-fuzz-build-logs.storage.googleapis.com/index.html>
dynamic_analysis_enable_assertions_justi: all asserts are enabled for tests in CI
dynamic_analysis_fixed_justification: they are mostly addressed before the PR lands
crypto_weaknesses_justification: Although Bittorrent widely rely on SHA-1, it is required by the protocol as it's currently defined and used. It's also believe to be less susceptible to the collision attack <https://github.com/bittorrent/bittorrent.org/issues/58#issuecomment-282143132>. There is work to transition to a version 2, using SHA-256.
test_continuous_integration_justificatio: appveyor <https://ci.appveyor.com/project/arvidn/libtorrent/history> for windows tests. travis for linux and mac <https://travis-ci.org/arvidn/libtorrent/pull_requests>. doozer for linux and mac <https://doozer.io/arvidn/libtorrent/builds>.
discussion_justification: GitHub supports discussions on issues and pull requests.
no_leaked_credentials_justification: there are no passwords or any key material in the repository (other than self-signed certificates used by the unit tests).
english_justification: All documentation, issues and code comments are in english: <https://libtorrent.org/reference.html>
hardened_site_justification: // X-Content-Type-Options was not set to "nosniff".
documentation_current_justification: Reference documentation is mostly embedded in the source code, to keep it tightly coupled with the actual logic.
accessibility_best_practices_justificati: There is no user interface, just API
internationalization_justification: There is no user interface, just API. The API does not use user-readable strings.
sites_password_security_justification: libtorrent does not provide any online accounts

report_tracker_justification: The project is using GitHub's issue tracking
report_process_justification: Users can report bugs and issues on https://github.com/rethinkdb/rethinkdb/issues
report_archive_justification: Since we are using GitHub, all the closed and open issues with the related responses can be found at https://github.com/rethinkdb/rethinkdb/issues
tests_documented_added_justification: Documentation of how to add tests: https://github.com/rethinkdb/rethinkdb/tree/next/test
crypto_call_justification:
Contains an implementation of SCRAM authentication, at https://github.com/rethinkdb/rethinkdb/blob/next/src/clustering/administration/auth/scram_authenticator.cc

Maybe this depends on what constitutes a cryptographic function, I'm taking the broader definition than just basic crypto primitives.
crypto_working_justification:
Probably the documentation at https://rethinkdb.com/api/javascript/uuid/ should mention that version 5 uuid's can't be considered guaranteed unique if they're computing based on user data, because they use SHA-1.

It's debatable whether this is a "security mechanism" -- it isn't advertised as one -- but the docs could be easily improved (with about one or two sentences).
crypto_pfs_justification: OpenSSL configured with perfect forward secrecy in mind at https://github.com/rethinkdb/rethinkdb/blob/next/src/clustering/administration/main/command_line.cc#L891
delivery_unsigned_justification: The software doesn't retrieve cryptographic hashes.  And the apt repo which checks the hash uses a cryptographic signature.
vulnerabilities_critical_fixed_justifica: This is unmet in the sense that 0/0 is a perfect record.  When a critical vulnerability is reported, then we'll see what the response time is.
static_analysis_fixed_justification: No vulnerability caught since it was introduced.
dynamic_analysis_enable_assertions_justi: There are plenty of run-time assertions, but they can't be checked during dynamic analysis if that is not run.
dynamic_analysis_fixed_justification: A dynamic analysis tool isn't run.
crypto_weaknesses_justification: I'd classify SHA-1 as broken, hence my response to the previous question.
discussion_justification: GitHub supports discussions on issues and pull requests.
no_leaked_credentials_justification: I'm assuming some level of competence by the team employed at RethinkDB before it shutdown, and have not audited the entirety of rethinkdb's repos.
hardened_site_justification: // X-Content-Type-Options was not set to "nosniff".
